A petrol engine is an internal combustion engine that uses petrol (gasoline) as fuel to produce power. It is commonly used in cars, motorcycles, generators, and small machines. 🚗🏍️

A petrol engine works using the Otto cycle, where fuel and air are mixed and ignited by a spark plug to create energy.

🔧 Main Parts of a Petrol Engine

Cylinder – Space where fuel burns

Piston – Moves up and down to create power

Spark Plug – Ignites the air-fuel mixture

Crankshaft – Converts piston movement into rotation

Valves – Control air and fuel flow

⚙️ Working of a Petrol Engine (4-Stroke Cycle)

Most petrol engines use the Four-stroke engine cycle.

1️⃣ Intake Stroke

The piston moves down.

Air and petrol mixture enters the cylinder.

2️⃣ Compression Stroke

The piston moves up.

The mixture is compressed.

3️⃣ Power Stroke

The spark plug ignites the mixture.

Explosion pushes the piston down, producing power. 🔥

4️⃣ Exhaust Stroke

The piston moves up again.

Burned gases exit through the exhaust valve.

🔹 Advantages of Petrol Engines

✔ Smooth and quiet operation
✔ Higher speed capability
✔ Lower vibration

🔹 Disadvantages

❌ Lower fuel efficiency than diesel
❌ Petrol cost is higher
❌ Less torque for heavy loads

🔹 Where Petrol Engines Are Used

Motorcycles

Cars

Small generators

Lawn mowers

Example: Many cars from Toyota and Honda use petrol engines.
